[2] Philippines (Nueva Ecija)
Date: Fri 29 Jul 2005
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Manila Bulletin, Philippines, 29 Jul 2005 [edited]
<http://www.mb.com.ph/PROV2005072940630.html>

Dengue outbreak downs at least 250 in Nueva Ecija, hardest-hit town
declared under state of emergency
-----------------------------------------------
A state of emergency has been declared in this town by local
officials, following a severe dengue fever outbreak that has claimed
the lives of 3 children and downed [infected] at least 117 other
persons. A 4th fatality was reported in Cuyapo town.
Dr. Benjamin Lopez, provincial health officer, had recorded between
250 and 300 dengue cases as of last Thursday [21 Jul 2005]. The cases
were reported to him by the various city and town health officers.
Doctor Lopez reported that, to date, at least 27 towns and 3 of the 5
cities of Nueva Ecija were affected by the mosquito-borne dengue
fever, with at least 250 reported cases. This town alone had 117
reported cases as of last Friday [22 Jul 2005].
Meanwhile, Mayor Isidro T. Pajarillaga allayed widespread fears that
the dengue fever outbreak in this town has gone out of control.
Pajarillaga said that he ordered, as far back as last February
[2005], fogging operations in all the barangays of the town, adding
that he has likewise ordered a repeat of the fogging operations every
Saturday in a bid to avert the spread of the disease.
The mayor said he recently discovered the other day that several
creeks and waterways in the town proper have been clogged by decaying
logs that were swept along by the series of typhoons last year
[2004]. He blamed some residents for the situation, saying that they
had been disposing of their garbage indiscriminately in places such
as canals and vacant lots, the reason why, at the onset of the rainy
season, the waterways were clogged and stagnant.
In a related development, some residents were alarmed by the reported
depletion of the PHP 2 million [USD 35 800] calamity fund at a time
when it is critically needed. Also, the residents have demanded the
presence of their mayor in the town to assist them in the emergency
situation.
In this regard, Pajarillaga said that he was in Manila recently to
follow up on the town's request to some congressmen and senators for
funding of the town's health programs, drainage projects and school
facilities. A request for assistance by a barangay captain for the
use of the town's ambulance was not granted due to lack of funds,
Pajarillaga said.
[Byline: Magtanggol C. Vilar]
